---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import CaseStudySnapshot from "@/components/CaseStudySnapshot.astro"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import homeVerdictImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/home-verdict.png"
import hourlyKitNumbersImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/hourly-kit-numbers.png"

const project = getProject("wheely-weather")!
const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [640, 960, 1280]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 768px) 960px, 100vw"

const snapshotItems = [
  {
    label: "Question",
    value: "Is it worth riding right now?",
  },
  {
    label: "Audience",
    value: "Recreational and commuter cyclists planning short-term rides.",
  },
  {
    label: "Core decision",
    value: "Let the weakest weather signal set the ride verdict.",
  },
  {
    label: "Built as",
    value:
      "Cross-platform Expo Router + React Native app (iOS, Android, web) from one codebase. Started as a web app; briefly explored native SwiftUI before consolidating on Expo.",
  },
]
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Wheely Weather"
  description="An independent cross-platform cycling-weather app, built with Expo for iOS, Android, and web, that puts dewpoint, feels-like temperature, and wind next to a clear ride verdict."
  seoTitle="Wheely Weather · Cross-Platform Cycling Weather App (Expo)"
  seoDescription="Wheely Weather is a cross-platform cycling weather app built with Expo for iOS, Android, and web, with ride-quality verdicts, hourly riding windows, and weather-based kit guidance."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Wheely Weather solves one near-term product decision: <em
      >is it worth going now?</em
    > General forecasts show plenty of numbers, but riders kept coming back to three
    signals: dew point, feels-like temperature, and wind.
  </p>
  <p>
    I designed the product around a clear verdict, visible evidence, and the
    next usable ride window when the answer is no. A web prototype validated the
    model before the cross-platform Expo build.
  </p>

  <CaseStudySnapshot items={snapshotItems} />

  <h2>The Decision Moment</h2>
  <p>
    Before a ride, I was checking one weather app and falling back to another.
    The data was available; the decision was not. Six conversations with
    recreational and commuter cyclists pointed to the same gap: dew point,
    feels-like temperature, and wind mattered, but dew point was easy to miss in
    the apps people already used.
  </p>
  <p>
    That set the product direction: put the useful signals beside the verdict,
    score by the weakest signal, and keep the whole experience glanceable on a
    phone.
  </p>

  <h2>Product Direction</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Lead with a five-level ride rating: Great, Good, Fair, Poor, or Bad.
    </li>
    <li>Let the weakest riding signal set the rating.</li>
    <li>Name the limiting condition when the ride rating drops.</li>
    <li>
      Keep the raw weather signals visible for riders who disagree with the
      recommendation.
    </li>
    <li>
      Point to the next usable window before asking anyone to study a chart.
    </li>
    <li>
      Guide kit selection from the same data, so no separate clothing app is
      needed.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <figure>
    <Picture
      src={homeVerdictImg}
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
      alt="Wheely Weather showing a green ‘CLEAR FOR RIDING’ ideal-conditions verdict for Portland, with the start of the hourly ride-quality chart below."
    />
    <figcaption>
      The verdict leads with color and plain language (green when it’s worth
      going, orange when it isn’t) and names the limiting factor when the answer
      is no.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2 id="system-design">System Design</h2>
  <p>
    The screen order follows the rider’s question sequence instead of the shape
    of a forecast API: can I go, why did it get that rating, what should I wear?
    The verdict card uses color and a plain-language label rather than a numeric
    score, so the app makes the threshold call instead of handing it back to the
    rider. The Numbers panel keeps the raw signals close enough to audit the
    recommendation.
  </p>
  <p>
    The design system carries this across platforms: a flat theme background,
    translucent glass-effect chrome for navigation and overlays, bold card
    surfaces (<code>BrutalCard</code>) for content, and the National Park
    typeface. Light and dark theming work throughout with no hardcoded colors,
    so the same component tree renders correctly on iOS, Android, and web.
  </p>

  <h2>Riding Windows</h2>
  <p>
    A bad current rating should still answer the next question. The hour-by-hour
    view turns “not now” into a specific window, showing ride quality tinted by
    temperature with a Now marker and POOR stickers on bad stretches. Below it,
    “Today’s kit” translates the same data into clothing guidance, and “The
    numbers” keeps every raw signal visible for riders who want to audit the
    verdict.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <Picture
      src={hourlyKitNumbersImg}
      formats={pictureFormats}
      widths={pictureWidths}
      sizes={pictureSizes}
      alt="Wheely Weather hour-by-hour ride-quality chart with a POOR sticker, Today’s kit guidance, and The numbers cards showing raw weather signals."
    />
    <figcaption>
      The hour-by-hour chart reads as a window, not a forecast: ride quality by
      hour, a Now marker, and kit guidance below.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Building Cross-Platform with Expo</h2>
  <p>
    One Expo Router + React Native codebase ships iOS, Android, and web. The web
    build is live at{" "}
    <a href="https://wheelyweather.app" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
      wheelyweather.app
    </a>{" "}
    on Cloudflare Workers.
  </p>
  <p>
    A shared, framework-agnostic TypeScript scoring domain in{" "}
    <code>src/domain/</code> holds the ride-quality logic and plain-language copy,
    feeding every platform from the same source. Theme-aware components drive the
    light/dark design system without hardcoded colors.
  </p>
  <p>
    Data comes from Open-Meteo by default, with Apple WeatherKit on iOS through
    a custom Expo native module (<code>modules/apple-weatherkit</code>).
    Geocoding uses Nominatim on web and Apple MapKit on iOS; AQI stays on
    Open-Meteo across all platforms. Acclimatization baselines come from 30 days
    of Open-Meteo temperatures.
  </p>
  <p>
    The idea started as an Astro/React web app that validated the verdict-first
    model, then a short native SwiftUI experiment. Consolidating on Expo gave
    one codebase across platforms without giving up native capabilities where
    they matter.
  </p>
  <p>
    The tooling pipeline keeps the build honest: Prettier, ESLint with{" "}
    <code>--max-warnings 0</code>, strict TypeScript, Vitest unit tests, a
    Storybook component workshop, Playwright end-to-end tests, and GitHub
    Actions CI. AI-assisted coding tools helped move faster from product
    sketches to working UI.
  </p>

  <h2>Outcome</h2>
  <p>
    I use the app across iOS and web before rides now. The single-codebase
    approach means a fix or feature ships across platforms at once, and the
    shared scoring domain keeps verdict behavior consistent on phone and web.
  </p>
  <p>
    The useful pattern was restraint: score the weakest signal, lead with a
    verdict, and keep the rest of the forecast in supporting roles.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
